Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.99,0:00:07.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.00,0:00:14.17,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.17,0:00:19.96,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled \Nnumerous lessons on how to live.{unsure, lit is "for the sake of living, precepts, numerous left behind"}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.37,0:00:31.39,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.89,0:00:42.98,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.98,0:00:50.95,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.95,0:00:59.24,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.24,0:01:06.69,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.69,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.89,0:01:49.10,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 16th, 1945, with the fall of Iwo Jima, the US Army \Nsecured a foothold for the invasion of mainland Japan.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.10,0:01:52.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Aiming to strengthen their position for a future invasion,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.50,0:02:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,an order to capture Okinawa was handed to the Commander-in-Chief of the US 5th Fleet, Admiral Spruance.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.48,0:02:09.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Under his command was the Fast Carrier Task Force, \Nled by Vice Admiral Mitscher.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.37,0:02:17.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Aside from that, was Task Force 54 under Rear Admiral Deyo: 10 battleships, 9 heavy cruisers, and 23 destroyers.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.72,0:02:23.38,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as British Carrier Force 57 \Nunder Vice Admiral Rawlings from the Royal Navy.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.38,0:02:33.72,Default,,0,0,0,,An enormous war fleet that totaled 1,317 ships, \N1,727 carrier-based aircraft, and 452,000 personnel.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.90,0:02:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,In contrast, the Japanese Combined Fleet Headquarters, \Nthat was confined to the mainland, {nc what to make of "located on land/陸上に置かれ"; probably something to do with "surface fleet"}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.66,0:02:44.05,Default,,0,0,0,,could only send a Surface Special Attack Force of the battleship Yamato,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.05,0:02:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,the light cruisers Yahagi, and 10 destroyers.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.38,0:02:55.41,Default,,0,0,0,,It was all that's left of the Combined Fleet that used to be \NJapan's pride ever since Admiral Togo started the tradition.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.41,0:03:01.62,Sign,,0,0,280,,{\c&HE4E6F8&\b1\blur1\bord0}Episode 24 \N{\fs90}The End of the Combined Fleet
Dialogue: 1,0:03:05.14,0:03:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, the US Marines approached Okinawa \Non April 1st, at 4:06 a.m., exactly as planned.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.14,0:03:10.89,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1000,0)\pos(626,177)}Okinawa
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.14,0:03:10.89,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1000,0)\pos(518,458)}East China Sea
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.89,0:03:17.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The landing party, under Lt. General Buckner, commander of the Tenth Army (TAF), began disembarking.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.70,0:03:27.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, it's eerily quiet down here. \NYou think the Japs are gone?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.47,0:03:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That's really strange. I thought their forte \Nwas fighting on the beaches.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.83,0:03:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Garrison commander Lieutenant General Ushijima,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.80,0:03:47.60,Default,,0,0,0,,who opted for a defense in depth,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.60,0:03:51.79,Default,,0,0,0,,was patiently waiting for the US Army \Nto proceed southwards.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.76,0:04:00.69,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.69,0:04:05.47,Default,,0,0,0,,this passive approach didn't sit well \Nwith the Combined Fleet High Command.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.47,0:04:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,So they decided to dispatch the 2nd Fleet, including Yamato, \Nthat was standing by off the coast of Mitajiri.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.58,0:04:24.02,Default,,0,0,0,,On April 6th, a strategy meeting was held on board Yamato \Nto work out the upcoming sortie.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.51,0:04:27.65,Default,,0,0,0,,That day, the special attendants \Nin charge of maintaining the morale
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.65,0:04:33.02,Default,,0,0,0,,were Chief of Staff Kusaka and Staff Officer Kami \Nfrom the Combined Fleet Headquarters. {says mikami but it's gotta be https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E7%A5%9E%E9%87%8D%E5%BE%B3}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.02,0:04:40.62,Default,,0,0,0,,As just explained by the Commander-in-Chief, \Nwe will only load enough fuel for a one way trip.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.62,0:04:43.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I would now ask you to look \Nat the documents you've been handed.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.80,0:04:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Before we begin this strategy meeting, \NI have a question.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.74,0:04:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Go ahead, Senior Staff Officer Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.60,0:04:49.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.89,0:04:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,My question is, seeing how you've come here \Nall the way from the Combined Fleet Headquarters today,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.66,0:04:57.61,Default,,0,0,0,,would you explain to us their intentions? {/High Command's}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.61,0:04:59.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Let's hear it out.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.54,0:05:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.80,0:05:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,It's alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.72,0:05:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Naturally, I have no objections to the special attack itself, \Nbut the ultimate objective of this order is unclear to me. {/suicide attack}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.09,0:05:19.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The order goes, \N"destroy enemy ships near Okinawa."
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.21,0:05:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,There's your objective.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.42,0:05:23.81,Default,,0,0,0,,But sir, is that objective really achievable?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.81,0:05:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,On the 8th, it'll already be a whole week \Nafter the enemy has landed.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.32,0:05:29.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Considering the resourcefulness of their CBs,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.57,0:05:34.03,Default,,0,0,0,,they'll have the air base repaired by then \Nand will unleash the full force of their air fleet upon us.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.03,0:05:38.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Besides, we estimate that the enemy \Nhas over 10 aircraft carriers in the area.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.12,0:05:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,By setting our time and course right into the enemy's ambush, we'll just serve ourselves up on a silver plate.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.44,0:05:45.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.82,0:05:49.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if we wanted to lure the enemy our way with a decoy,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.06,0:05:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,so as to prevent the troops from landing, the 8th day is too late!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.46,0:05:57.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Aren't headquarters just clutching at straws, \Ncalling things such lofty names as "Special Attack Fleet"? {not sure what he means: 名前だけ 艦隊特攻という美名に 溺れておるんじゃないかね 司令部は}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.79,0:05:59.29,Default,,0,0,0,,They definitely aren't!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.29,0:06:01.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't it just a thought exercise from headquarters? {lit: is it an HQ's whimsical/idea strategy}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.48,0:06:02.23,Default,,0,0,0,,What?!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.23,0:06:05.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I have all I need to know. \NPerhaps you're right, after all. {no clue whose side he's one, lit is "it migh just turn out exactly tht way"}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.00,0:06:24.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Ito, the proposal to use Yamato in this way also faced strong opposition within the Combined Fleet Headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.87,0:06:27.98,Default,,0,0,0,,With barely any fuel and no air support. {/one way trip's worth of fuel}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.98,0:06:31.76,Default,,0,0,0,,They can tout it as unsinkable all they want, \Nit's still a plan of desperation.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.76,0:06:37.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, even though you know that, I want you to understand the circumstances that made this plan our only option.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.33,0:06:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,It has been a long time since we last drank together.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.62,0:06:45.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Okinawa is a crucial position. Losing it now \Nwould mean the inevitable defeat of Japan in the war. {strategic point; crucial time; watershed; crunch​}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.64,0:06:50.16,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll lose even if 100 million \Ngo out on a suicide attack at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.16,0:06:52.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The reasons for it are aplenty. {this decision to send yamato}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.16,0:06:53.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But I'm not here to talk about that.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.78,0:06:56.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Just think of it as a forerunner \Nto that 100 million suicide attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.95,0:06:59.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, the Commander-in-Chief of the Combined Fleet Toyoda
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.75,0:07:03.69,Default,,0,0,0,,said he wanted to let the flowers \Nof our precious Yamato bloom at least once.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.38,0:07:05.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Let her flowers bloom?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.48,0:07:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.55,0:07:13.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.22,0:07:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,If we make it out, why don't we go get \NTogakushi soba again one day? {not a company name, but a province where they make it}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.85,0:07:21.05,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd sure like to. {/well said}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.30,0:07:31.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Come in.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.91,0:07:34.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah. Sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.22,0:07:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't mind me? {/can I enter/talk to you}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.12,0:07:36.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course not.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.91,0:07:38.66,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm at your service whenever you need me.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.66,0:07:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You sure cleaned it up nicely. \NAnd this one has such a fine face.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.84,0:07:43.77,Default,,0,0,0,,With it, I feel at ease.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.77,0:07:45.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you still smoking these days?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.63,0:07:48.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. No matter what I do. I can't go \Nwithout at least 100 a day.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.63,0:07:51.09,Default,,0,0,0,,That's way above the ration, I reckon.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.09,0:07:52.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I got this one from the enemy.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.40,0:07:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.49,0:07:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Say, Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.89,0:07:58.58,Default,,0,0,0,,You probably see my decision to accept \Nthis suicide assignment as erroneous?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.52,0:08:02.49,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.49,0:08:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't need to be concerned about that.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.70,0:08:07.50,Default,,0,0,0,,I hear that your son \Nalso volunteered to join the special attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.50,0:08:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,That's true. But I came here to tell you \Nthat there's one more agenda I'm pursuing. {/objective}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.70,0:08:12.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.47,0:08:16.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly, we may get sunk on the way, just as you say.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.12,0:08:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,But I want to lead us to the shores of Okinawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.59,0:08:25.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Floating or beached, I want to fire our battery \Nof the world's largest 46 cm cannons one more time. {actually says just "floating battery" but he gotta mean this - a battery that can sail to its destination}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.18,0:08:26.90,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what I thought too.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.90,0:08:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's make it there, whatever it takes.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.88,0:08:31.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever it takes! {/do something}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.29,0:08:32.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.80,0:08:40.45,Default,,0,0,0,,In response to the HQ's thought exercise, \Nthe 2nd Fleet made a secret decision before sortieing.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.44,0:08:44.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Vice Admiral Ito signaled to the armada his instructions,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.81,0:08:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,worthy of a historical sortie\Nthat would be remembered for years to come.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.72,0:08:51.78,Default,,0,0,0,,"A miraculous feat lies right ahead of us. {https://xn--ww2-523es33s4hr4hk.jp/kantaisen26.htm - 神機将ニ動カントス。皇国ノ隆替繋リテ此ノ一挙ニ存ス。各員奮戦激闘会敵ヲ必滅シ以テ海上特攻隊ノ本領ヲ発揮セヨ - a little unsure about the whole quote, as very solemn archaic style}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.78,0:08:55.14,Default,,0,0,0,,The prosperity of the motherland hinges on this one battle.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.60,0:09:00.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Let everyone fight hard, fight ferociously, \Nand reduce the enemy to nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.16,0:09:04.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Show everyone that the Naval Special Attack Corps \Nis a force to be reckoned with."
Dialogue: 1,0:09:31.78,0:09:38.29,Default,,0,0,0,,By the time they exited the Bungo Channel, \NYamato was already shadowed by an enemy submarine.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.78,0:09:39.70,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\c&HFAE0E9&\3c&HC96D57&\pos(700,794)}Cape Toi
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.78,0:09:39.70,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\c&HFAE0E9&\3c&H4DA1B6&\pos(512,280)}Kyushu
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.78,0:09:39.70,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\c&HFAE0E9&\3c&H4DA1B6&\pos(626,54)}Mitajiri
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.78,0:09:39.70,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\c&HFAE0E9&\3c&H4DA1B6&\pos(969,164)}Shikoku
Dialogue: 1,0:09:38.29,0:09:42.04,Default,,0,0,0,,This ill omen was a precursor \Nto the difficulties still ahead. {lit: so soon, but it already made them thought that the future is full of trouble}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.84,0:10:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Around that time, the task force in charge of supporting the Okinawa landings under Admiral Spruance
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.94,0:10:06.99,Default,,0,0,0,,came under attack from 400 Japanese kamikaze planes \Nthat took off from Kanoya and other bases.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.99,0:10:11.38,Default,,0,0,0,,He was swamped with commanding and administrative work, so he was having a late dinner.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.93,0:10:15.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I apologize for interrupting your meal.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.22,0:10:18.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Never mind it. What did you want, Davis?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.43,0:10:19.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I've just completed this report. {assuming he came to give spruance this sheet in his hands, lit is ambiguous: 今済ませたところです / just finished now}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.95,0:10:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,They sure gave us a run for our money today. \NWho knew the Japanese still have more of such pilots. {lit: it was a terrible experience today, turns out there are still such planes in japan?}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.39,0:10:26.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. I was just as surprised.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.31,0:10:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's the promised gift \Nfrom Tokyo Rose, the kamikaze?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.26,0:10:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,That time around, the damage from the kamikaze attack \Nwas: 3 destroyers, 1 LST, and 2 ammunition ships sunk.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.23,0:10:51.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The light carrier San Jacinto, 15 destroyers,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.06,0:10:53.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and 4 minesweepers heavily damaged. {actually gekiha is "crushing" but San Jacinto was in fact not damaged at all irl lmao}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.23,0:10:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,In the confusion,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.44,0:11:04.33,Default,,0,0,0,,the battleship North Carolina, the light cruiser Burnett, 2 transport ships, and one LST were damaged by friendly fire. {now this is even better - USS Burnett is nonexistent, there was never any ship in the world with such name or anything even remotely similar to it}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.88,0:11:09.91,Default,,0,0,0,,One more transport ship \Nwas reportedly damaged in a collision.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.91,0:11:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,That said, there's also some news that'll cheer you up.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.75,0:11:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.61,0:11:16.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Your beloved one is coming.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.61,0:11:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Beloved one?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.13,0:11:22.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Yamato has finally left port, \Nas reported by the submarine Threadfin. {Name checks out https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Threadfin}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.62,0:11:27.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I see now. My beloved one indeed. \NHow should we welcome her? Signal a strategy meeting. {lit: let's go to the operations room}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.77,0:11:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Is this all the reports on the Japanese fleet we have?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.49,0:11:31.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.75,0:11:36.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Very well. Then, we can draw \N2 conclusions from from these reports.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.32,0:11:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,First one is that Yamato is out of port.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.59,0:11:43.82,Default,,0,0,0,,The other one is that the enemy's surface fleet \Nhas been reduced to a dozen of ships.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.82,0:11:45.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.65,0:11:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So tell me this, Davis.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.23,0:11:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,We are now faced with one choice to make \Nand one predicament to solve.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.73,0:11:58.34,Default,,0,0,0,,The choice being "by what means \Nshould we go about defeating Yamato?"
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.34,0:12:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And the predicament being \Ndetermining Yamato's true destination.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.26,0:12:06.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand why you see Yamato's destination as a problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.48,0:12:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,But what do you mean by "choosing the means to..."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.25,0:12:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Should we sink her with an overwhelming air attack,\Nlike what happened with Musashi and Prince of Wales?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.77,0:12:15.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Or should we give her one more naval battle? {... decisive}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.77,0:12:17.44,Default,,0,0,0,,You mean a surface fleet engagement?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.06,0:12:22.21,Default,,0,0,0,,As this report states, the enemy is completely exposed, \Nwithout a single plane to cover them.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.96,0:12:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But in a surface fleet engagement, Yamato will have a chance to use their cannons, the largest in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.76,0:12:30.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, that's what I'll do.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.29,0:12:30.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.74,0:12:35.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Ever since the Prince of Wales \Nsank at the hands of an air attack,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.75,0:12:39.71,Default,,0,0,0,,it is unthinkable that you can conduct \Na decisive naval battle without airplanes.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.34,0:12:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, Admiral Spruance elected to settle it \Nwith an old-fashioned decisive naval battle of surface fleets.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.19,0:12:49.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Who knows why he made such a decision?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.60,0:13:01.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral Spruance's decision to dispatch a surface fleet \Nto engage Yamato in a decisive naval battle was transmitted
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.09,0:13:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,to the Gunfire and Covering force 54 under Rear Admiral Deyo and Fast Carrier Force 58 under Vice Admiral Mitscher.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.97,0:13:12.29,Default,,0,0,0,,That's ridiculous! The defining force \Nof modern naval warfare is aircraft carriers!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.29,0:13:13.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that right, Burke?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.66,0:13:18.79,Default,,0,0,0,,A surface engagement or not, our Air Fleet \Nis only delegated the auxiliary role of dealing light jabs?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.79,0:13:20.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The old man must be going senile.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.21,0:13:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.00,0:13:24.32,Default,,0,0,0,,The honor of defeating Yamato, \Nthe embodiment of the Japanese naval spirit,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.32,0:13:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,naturally belongs to carriers, \Nthe embodiment of the American naval spirit!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.49,0:13:29.51,Default,,0,0,0,,It has to be our Task Force 58!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.51,0:13:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,What's a good way to do it?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.70,0:13:34.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, Admiral Spruance allowed us to make a jab.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.43,0:13:38.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Not an uppercut, for sure. But with enough speed, \Neven just one jab is enough to knock the opponent down.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.31,0:13:42.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the "31-knot" Burke I know! {it was his nickname}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.48,0:13:53.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, got it. I'll let the admiral know.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.41,0:13:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Rear Admiral Deyo reports. It seems that everyone \Nis in high spirits and celebrating already.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.52,0:14:01.96,Default,,0,0,0,,They wanted to give you a thousand thanks.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.96,0:14:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,I see, they're happy with it too? \NWell, it's only natural.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.27,0:14:08.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Battleships should fight other battleships.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.02,0:14:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I know we should support the landing party, but their skills would blunt from shooting at land targets all the time. {to become useless; to blunt; to weaken (from lack of practice)}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.47,0:14:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,It was 38 years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.38,0:14:22.82,Default,,0,0,0,,When I just graduated from the Annapolis Naval Academy \NI went to Japan with the Great White Fleet expedition. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_White_Fleet ; btw I'm sure they mistook the hair color of these two in this shot}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.84,0:14:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,There, I've met Admiral Togo himself.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.03,0:14:33.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And it was not just me. He was an object of admiration \Nfor all of us naval officers.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.04,0:14:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We were also taught Togo's stratagems.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And we went to see Japanese sumo.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.40,0:14:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,That's when... they're fighting naked?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.90,0:14:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Right. And when you defeat a mentor who taught you, \Nthey call it returning the favor.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.38,0:14:50.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, the one defeated \Nshould give his blessing to his trainee.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.91,0:14:52.91,Default,,0,0,0,,To think you know even such minutia... {lit: there's even such a thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.91,0:14:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,That's exactly what I want to do now.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.60,0:14:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Return the favor to the Japanese fleets \Nthat Togo brought up.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.60,0:15:07.42,Default,,0,0,0,,With no way of knowing that Admiral Spruance made \Nthat kind of decision and was now preparing to meet her,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.42,0:15:10.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamato proceeded on her peaceful voyage.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.93,0:15:12.70,Default,,0,0,0,,The clouds are thick today.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.70,0:15:16.69,Default,,0,0,0,,If this keeps up, the enemy \Nwill have a hard time attacking us.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.69,0:15:18.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy aircraft!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.58,0:15:21.54,Default,,0,0,0,,General quarters! All hands! {no clue whatsoever, same in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.13,0:15:41.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare for anti-aircraft warfare!{believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.26,0:15:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Contact! 31 degrees 22 minutes north latitude, \N129 degrees 14 minutes east longitude!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.43,0:16:01.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamato-class battleship - 1 or 2, 8 destroyers. \NCourse 300, speed 12 knots!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.32,0:16:09.53,Default,,0,0,0,,A full-scale air raid is coming now. {nc what he means by "there is ...."}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.38,0:16:14.39,Default,,0,0,0,,With their course of 300...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.76,0:16:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Where is Yamato going, really?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.03,0:16:19.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Doesn't seem to be Okinawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.43,0:16:20.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe Sasebo?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.04,0:16:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't let her escape!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.59,0:16:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Is there a way to chase her?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.06,0:16:29.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Well... Our planes can probably catch up with her. \NThe rest of the battlefleet, though...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.59,0:16:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Impossible, then?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.44,0:16:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.11,0:16:34.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Vice Admiral Mitscher on the line.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.70,0:16:37.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.85,0:16:39.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello, Mark?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.27,0:16:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello, Ray.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.58,0:16:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Doing it with a surface fleet, after all?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.66,0:16:44.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Mark, of course we will.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.73,0:16:49.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Really? The enemy seems to be heading to Sasebo. \NCan you catch up with them?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.63,0:16:51.31,Default,,0,0,0,,What do I say? Can we catch up?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.26,0:16:54.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Hard to tell...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.72,0:16:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, an internal conflict \Nwas tearing Spruance apart.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.80,0:17:01.13,Default,,0,0,0,,But someone had to make this decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.62,0:17:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,If they miss their chance now, \Nwould they come across Yamato ever again?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.22,0:17:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But at the same time, it pained him to let Yamato \Nfall prey to aviation.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.76,0:17:17.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello? Hello! Ray, are you there?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.99,0:17:20.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Please let me sink the world's biggest battleship! {actually just "world's #1 giant" but because ships are females in english, can't make it "son of a bitch/bastard"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.95,0:17:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Fine. Do it!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.29,0:17:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.28,0:17:29.78,Default,,0,0,0,,What should we say to Deyo?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.77,0:17:32.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Nothing. Let them proceed as is.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.86,0:17:35.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Even a fella as aggressive as Mark \Ncan't do it in this weather.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.68,0:17:41.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The clouds are low and the visibility is just 5 or 6 miles. \NThis incapacitates their planes. They can't dive safely. {/swoop}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.67,0:17:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,All combat-ready aircraft \Nof TF 58.1, 58.3, and 58.4 take off immediately!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.94,0:17:57.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Time is 9:40 a.m.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.25,0:18:00.09,Default,,0,0,0,,If you take off by 10, \Nyou'll make it there for the enemy's lunch.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.09,0:18:03.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But you'll come with some gifts. \NYou're uninvited guests, after all. {/bring along a souvenir}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.29,0:18:06.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, don't come back \Nuntil Yamato hits the seabed!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.74,0:18:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll say it once again. \NDon't come back until Yamato is on the seabed! {not sure what's zenki here and in prev.}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.30,0:19:06.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Incited by "31-knot" Burke's inflammatory speech, \N280 aircraft took flight. {no clue what to make of 悪性に送られて / sent to burke's evil speaking}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.39,0:19:12.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Just as Admiral Spruance noted, \Nthat attack was anything but easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.76,0:19:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Some later compared it to swimming in pottage. {thick soup}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.20,0:19:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy contact! Larger formation than before! {nc whats hosaku and word after it, mokuhyo is target; could be izuremo - any; all; every; both; either; none (with neg. verb)}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.37,0:19:32.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy planes approaching! {nc whats isshusai, beliving HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.30,0:19:33.79,Default,,0,0,0,,General quarters! {nc}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.13,0:19:52.22,Default,,0,0,0,,335 degrees!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.22,0:19:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Next target: 250, 85 degrees! {literal}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.79,0:20:31.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Fire!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.28,0:22:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,So I guess we won't get to become the Okinawan shore battery. {"floating battery" again}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.96,0:22:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. We failed to keep our mission secret. {/decision }
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.30,0:22:33.16,Default,,0,0,0,,You haven't smoked at all today.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.60,0:22:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I decided to abstain until we become a shore battery.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.81,0:22:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Just as I thought. \NYou didn't want to jinx it? {lit: "you kept your decision secret?" - no clue what's connection between that and him not smoking}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.78,0:23:02.02,Default,,0,0,0,,April 7th, 2:23 p.m.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.02,0:23:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,30 degrees 20 minutes north latitude, \N128 degrees 4 minutes east longitude.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.26,0:23:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,200 nautical miles north \Nof Tokunoshima Island in Kyushu region,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.59,0:23:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,in the East China Sea, at the depth of 480 meters, \NYamato found her final resting place. {/sank}
Dialogue: 1,0:23:18.52,0:23:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the Japanese Combined Fleet, proud of its glorious traditions, dating back to Admiral Togo himself,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\frz343\pos(556,824)}Yamato
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\pos(823,790)\frz340.6}Yahagi
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\pos(775,584)\frz339.3}Isokaze
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\pos(618,126)\frz338.6}Asashimo
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\frz338\pos(550,258)}Kasumi
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.35,0:23:25.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(400,0)\c&HFBFAFF&\bord0\blur1\frz337.6\pos(829,382)}Hamakaze
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.71,0:23:29.72,Default,,0,0,0,,has well and truly found its end here.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.15,0:23:37.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese Navy doctrine of heavy ships and big guns \Nwas mercilessly swallowed up in the whirlpool of history.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.65,0:23:45.21,Default,,0,0,0,,But at the same time, we can reflect upon \Nthe horrible consequences of such a reactionary approach. {lit: what a dreadful stuff the decision that doesn't listen/consult the prospects/outlook / 見通しのきかなくなった決断が}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.67,0:23:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as upon the decisions taken by the Americans
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.01,0:23:56.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and their firm determination to act upon it afterwards, \Nwithout which any decision making is ultimately pointless. {very diff. sentence, unsure as a whole: それと同時に見通しのきかなくなった決断がいかに恐ろしいものなのか そしてアメリカ側の決断からは決断の後には果敢な実行力がなければならないということを学び取ることができる}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.83,0:24:07.59,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.24,0:24:12.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Morning of July 27, 1945.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.84,0:24:19.56,Default,,0,0,0,,A joint declaration from the US, UK, and China - \Nthe Potsdam Declaration was radioed to Japan last night.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.04,0:24:23.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And to add to her miseries, \Nan atomic bomb is dropped.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.46,0:24:26.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Would we accept the Potsdam Declaration, \Nor defend the mainland to the last?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.91,0:24:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Witness the hardships and decisions of the intelligence bureau chief Shimomura from Suzuki Kantaro's cabinet
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.61,0:24:35.70,Default,,0,0,0,,in the next Decision: \NThe Final Decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.61,0:24:38.21,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 25\NThe Final Decision
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.62,0:24:48.59,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.59,0:24:52.59,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.59,0:24:56.84,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.84,0:25:05.34,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.34,0:25:13.83,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
